explanation:
To determine whether any part of OS_MutSemGive is unreachable you must know which control-flow paths and values are possible and what macros/types expand to. Brief reasons:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Primary decision point — the if-body is conditional on its return. Must inspect implementation to see whether OS_SUCCESS can ever be returned for the given arguments.
- OS_SUCCESS: The value compared against return_code; needed to evaluate the conditional.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The arguments passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById can affect its behavior and thus reachability of the if-body.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are direct callees used inside OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the static graph). Their behaviour influences whether OS_ObjectIdGetById can return OS_SUCCESS.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used inside the if-body to obtain the mutex record; its expansion may introduce side-effects or different indexing that affect reachability analysis.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Often used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET expansions; needed to understand how token maps to table index and whether that access is well-defined.
- OS_mutex_table: The object table referenced by the macro; needed to understand whether the table and index access are valid and if any invariants prevent execution of the block.
- OS_mutex_internal_record_t: Type of the table entries; required to see the last_owner field accessed in the if-body and any constraints on its values.
- OS_object_token_t, osal_id_t: Types for token and sem_id/self_task; required for type/representation semantics and any macros/functions operating on them.
- OS_TaskGetId: Called inside the if-body; to determine if any side-effects or special semantics could affect reachability or be involved in implicit control flow.
- OS_ObjectIdEqual: Used to compare last_owner and self_task in the if-body; its semantics (e.g., always true/false under some representations) affect whether code in the conditional warning path is reachable.
- OS_ObjectIdToInteger, OS_DEBUG: Used in the debug message; include to check whether the debug call could alter control flow or have side-effects that influence reachability.
- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED: Assigned to last_owner in the if-body; needed to understand whether the assignment is meaningful or could be optimized away or constrained by invariants.
- OS_MutSemGive_Impl: Final call inside the if-body; include to see whether the body has observable effects or whether callers/implementations make the body redundant.

Together these symbols let the next analyst inspect the implementation and macro expansions that determine whether the conditional block can ever execute; that is required to decide if any code within OS_MutSemGive is unreachable (MISRA rule violation).
